<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by john_tent on 04-24-2001 06:28 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">I have been following the boards for a while now and still have a few questions as to how items are tracked by Verant. While most agree that there is some type of Database that keeps track of item transfers, the specifics seem to be unknown

Hence if you have answers to these question feel free to reply.

1.	Items, do they have a specific number that makes them unique. 
I.e. A blue diamond has number 30000004 and another blue diamond has 30000012? If no, does that apply for all items, or do the more rare or ueber items have unique numbers? In a very recent post somebody said that was not the case, but again, it was only one person who said that.

2.	How are items kept track of?
Is there a record per character or per item? ( Without a specific number system it would make more sense that it was kept per person) 
I.e. Record “KING” entry 1. Looted a “diamond”
      Record “ FRIEND” entry 1. Received a “diamond from character “KING”
 	Record “KING” entry 2. Traded diamond to “FRIEND”

3.	Is the zone and time items were traded/dropped part of the record? 
I would assume yes but anybody know for sure?
4.	If I drop a “DIAMOND” with ”CHARACTER A” and pick up the same “DIAMOND” with “CHARACTER B”, can Verant search the database by checking where CHARACTER A dropped the “DIAMOND” and then do a search as to who picked up the “DIAMOND”. ( If they log time and zone, it will narrow down the search, especially on rare items that probably weren’t dropped on the ground in that zone for a long time)

Now I am sure most people are convinced everything is logged, however 2 things make me not so sure.

Not being a coder I don’t know how much stress such log keeping would put on a system, but with thousands of players and millions of transaction, it seems the demand would be very excessive. Therefore it might not warrant the extra cost of keeping such an elaborate database in operation.

Finally, if they do keep track of everything, have records and proof of all the transactions, how come that it seems like they do not actually use the data in item disputes? If you don’t bitch enough you don’t get what you lost even if you did really lose the item. However if you make yourself a serious pain you do get your way. And from what I have read and heard I believe that to be the case even if the item never existed.
</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
